<h2>How the Three Peptides Work Together</h2>

<p>The synergy here is not just marketing language. Each peptide addresses a genuine bottleneck in the healing cascade, and the combination covers gaps that any single compound leaves open.</p>

<table class="tbl">
<thead><tr><th>Healing Stage</th><th>BPC-157</th><th>TB-500</th><th>GHK-Cu</th></tr></thead>
<tbody>
<tr><td><strong>Hours 0-72</strong></td><td class="g">Reduces inflammation, initiates angiogenesis</td><td class="g">Begins cell migration signaling</td><td class="y">Protects cells from oxidative damage</td></tr>
<tr><td><strong>Days 3-14</strong></td><td class="g">New blood vessels forming</td><td class="g">Repair cells arriving at injury</td><td class="g">Collagen production ramping up</td></tr>
<tr><td><strong>Weeks 2-6</strong></td><td class="y">Tendon/ligament strengthening</td><td class="g">Scar tissue reduction</td><td class="g">Structural remodeling underway</td></tr>
<tr><td><strong>Weeks 6+</strong></td><td class="y">Maintenance support</td><td class="y">Flexibility improvement</td><td class="g">Tissue maturation and quality</td></tr>
</tbody>
</table>

<p>BPC-157 works locally, concentrating its effects near the injection site. TB-500 works systemically, sending repair signals throughout the body. GHK-Cu focuses on the structural endgame, ensuring that new tissue is strong and properly organized rather than weak scar tissue.</p>

<div class="d-p">
  <div class="s">Why Stacking Outperforms Single Peptides</div>
  <p>Think of it like a construction project. BPC-157 builds the roads (blood vessels). TB-500 brings in the workers (cell migration). GHK-Cu provides the building materials (collagen, elastin). Skip any one of these and the project slows down. Together, they create a more complete repair response than any single peptide can achieve alone.</p>
</div>

